# React MUI Redux Development Guidelines

## Critical Rules

### Package Management and Analysis
- ALWAYS analyze requirements thoroughly before implementation to identify potential existing packages that could reduce development effort
- ALWAYS use yarn instead of npm for package management
- Document any new package additions with clear justification in commit messages

### File Structure and Types
- Use .jsx extension for all React component files
- Remove all TypeScript configurations and dependencies
- Convert any existing .tsx files to .jsx
- Remove types/ directory and all type definitions
- Update build configurations to remove TypeScript support

### Development Workflow
- Before implementing new features:
  1. Analyze requirements in detail
  2. Research existing packages that could fulfill requirements
  3. Document package selection rationale
  4. Present package options if multiple viable solutions exist
- Maintain consistent code style without TypeScript annotations
- Use PropTypes for component prop validation instead of TypeScript interfaces

### Package Installation
- Use yarn commands exclusively:
  - `yarn add [package]` for new dependencies
  - `yarn add -D [package]` for dev dependencies
  - `yarn remove [package]` for removing packages
  - `yarn` to install all dependencies

## Examples

<example>
// Good practice - Using existing package for complex functionality
// Instead of implementing a custom date picker:
yarn add @mui/x-date-pickers

// Component using the package
import { DatePicker } from '@mui/x-date-pickers';

function BookingForm() {
  return (
    <DatePicker
      label="Select Date"
      onChange={handleDateChange}
      renderInput={(params) => <TextField {...params} />}
    />
  );
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// Bad practice - Not utilizing existing packages
// Implementing custom date picker from scratch
class CustomDatePicker extends React.Component {
  // Complex custom implementation
  // Reinventing the wheel instead of using @mui/x-date-pickers
}

// Bad practice - Using npm instead of yarn
npm install some-package

// Bad practice - Using TypeScript
interface Props {
  date: Date;
  onChange: (date: Date) => void;
}
</example>
